ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

Vigor of Activity(Hippity Hop): Interval 1 Epoch 1
Notes: 0 = Extremely low vigor: Very little movement; looking at the stimulus and possibly touching it; 1 = Low vigor: Sitting on the Hippity Hop; rocking back and forth; tapping Hippity Hop lightly with hands; 2 = Moderate vigor: A little more active movement; jumping in the immediate area; 3 = High vigor: Jumping actively; mainly jumping up and down rather than traversing room; tossing or bouncing the Hippity Hop around room; 4 = Extremely high vigor: Jumping actively and continuously; mainly traversing room and jumping high; really using legs to propel self. Slamming Hippity Hop against wall or ceiling; swinging or throwing Hippity Hop over head.

Vigor of Activity(Rest Time): Interval 1 Epoch 1
Notes:
0 = No vigor: No movement at all; 1 = Extremely low vigor: Partial body movement. Laying or sitting still;
minimal movement. Fidgeting is included under this category; 2 = Low vigor: Some movement; moves in immediate area; 3 = Moderate vigor: Walks around the room; 4 = High vigor: Increased movements; bouncing; moving in a rapid manner; 5 = Extremely high vigor: Rapid movements; running; jumping; moving quickly around the room.

ElementDescription: Number of manipulated objects(Workbench):: Interval 4 Average
Vigor of activity(Workbench): Interval 1 Epoch 1
Notes: 0 = Extremely low vigor: Little or no hand movement; looking at the workbench. No active involvement with bench; 1 = Low vigor: Little hand movement; looking at the workbench and possibly touching one or two accessories. Holding an object and perhaps manipulating it; but not using it in conjunction with another object; or to manipulate another object. Quiet manipulation of stimuli; minimal movement in general; 2 = Moderate vigor: A little more movement than just quiet manipulation; moving hands at a medium pace to manipulate objects. Manipulating screws at a medium pace. Weak hammering; 3 = High vigor: Actively playing with more than one object from the workbench; moving hands at a quick pace to manipulate objects; hammering at a high intensity. Manipulating screws at a fast pace; 4 = Extremely high vigor: Actively playing with many workbench accessories; using hand to manipulate objects very quickly. Pounding or manipulating accessories or bench with forcefulness.

Compliance(Story Time):
Overall rating of contentedness(Story Time): Experimenter
Notes:
0 = Extremely low level of contentment: C treats telling the story as a chore
rather than a fun activity; C may rush through the book; 1 = Low level of contentment: C shows very little enjoyment in telling the story; C may act disinterested or become easily distracted; 2 = Moderate level of contentment: C enjoys telling the story and is engaged in telling it; but shows less pleasure when asked to retell the story to the parent; 3 = High level of contentment: C remains highly engaged and exhibits pleasure
during almost the entire episode; C enjoys telling the story to both the
experimenter and the parent.

ElementDescription: Parent Behavior(Painting/drawing a picture)
Notes: 0 = Not interfering; neutral; 1 = Mild interference; 1-2 low level comments or adjustment of C; 2 = Interfering; emotionally loaded statements to C; reprimanding C; commanding; soothing; or generally disrupting

ElementDescription: Frequency of reaches to midline(Hand preference):
Notes: when C reaches for crayon the reach is considered within their midline if it is within two crayons outside of their ears (their midlines)

ElementDescription: Frequency of draws(Hand preference)
Notes: Code every time C draws on the paper (if C colors all over paper but never lifts the crayon, it is only one draw)

ElementDescription: Number of shifts(Hand preference):
Notes:
One shift is defined as shifting the crayon from one hand to
the other and then drawing

ElementDescription: Number of box grips(Hand preference):
Notes: Number of times C holds the box as he/she puts crayons away is coded for each hand

ElementDescription: Number of paper holds(Hand Preference):
Notes: Number of times C uses each hand to hold down the paper while he/she draws is coded

ElementDescription: Number of crayons placed back in box(Hand preference):
Notes: The number of crayons C places back in the box with each hand is coded
